				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok…I will have to admit that I cheated with one game, Diablo two. Who did not cheat with this game? I cheated within that game for two reasons:
<br />

<br />
1)To get revenge, on all the other hacked players!
<br />
2)To actually <span style="font-weight: bold">LEARN</span> how to hack!
<br />

<br />
To my surprise after I taught myself Hex coding, picked on a few people, and got my revenge I did not want to play the game anymore. Why did the game become boring?
<br />

<br />
1)I had everything, and I did not have to interact in order to trade.
<br />
2)I did not have to kill anything in order to receive items.
<br />
3)I could kill anything, in any level without effort.
<br />
4)All the duels were who ever hit first; basically they were skill-less fights!
<br />

<br />
Can we really be surprised that people want to cheat in order to win, or make the game easier? No, it happens in all aspects of life. Whether it is sports, board games, gambling, buying a car, or <span style="font-weight: bold">war</span> majority of people try to find a method to get a leg up on the competition. 
<br />

<br />
We cannot complain if a game sets itself up to be hacked, all we can do is smile and find another game. It is up to the game manufacturers, which produce online games, to create systems that make it very difficult to hack. Everquest has managed to keep hacking down to a minimum…now to stop twinking, but I would loose 10 characters…rofl!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
